theory.content:
CSS Media Queries are a CSS3 module that allow content rendering to adapt to various conditions (e.g., screen resolution, orientation, color scheme). They are a cornerstone of responsive web design, enabling developers to apply different styles based on the characteristics of the device or browsing environment.

### Basic Syntax

A media query consists of a media type (e.g., `screen`, `print`) and zero or more media feature expressions (e.g., `min-width`, `orientation`).

```css
@media <media-type> and (<media-feature>) {
  /* CSS rules to apply */
}
```

### Common Media Types

*   `all`: Suitable for all devices.
*   `print`: For paged material and documents viewed on a screen in print preview mode.
*   `screen`: For color computer screens.
*   `speech`: For speech synthesizers.

### Media Feature Examples:

*   **Width/Height Based Breakpoints:**
    *   `min-width`: Applies styles when the viewport is at least a specified width.
    *   `max-width`: Applies styles when the viewport is at most a specified width.
    *   `width`: Applies styles when the viewport is exactly a specified width.

    ```css
    /* Base styles for mobile devices */
    body {
      font-size: 16px;
    }

    /* Tablet devices: viewport at least 768px wide */
    @media (min-width: 768px) {
      body {
        font-size: 18px;
      }
    }

    /* Desktop devices: viewport at least 1024px wide */
    @media (min-width: 1024px) {
      body {
        font-size: 20px;
      }
    }
    ```

*   **Orientation:**
    *   `orientation: landscape`: Applied when the viewport is wider than it is tall.
    *   `orientation: portrait`: Applied when the viewport is taller than it is wide.

    ```css
    @media (orientation: landscape) {
      /* Applied when viewport is in landscape orientation */
      menu {
        float: left;
      }
    }
    ```

*   **User Preferences:**
    *   `prefers-color-scheme: dark`: Applied when the user has dark mode enabled in their operating system or browser settings.
    *   `prefers-color-scheme: light`: Applied when the user has light mode enabled.

    ```css
    @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
      /* Applied when user has dark mode enabled */
      body {
        background-color: #333;
        color: #eee;
      }
    }
    ```

*   **Device Aspect Ratio:**
    *   `device-aspect-ratio`: Targets the ratio of the device's screen width to height.

    ```css
    /* For displays with 16:9 aspect ratio */
    @media screen and (device-aspect-ratio: 16/9) {
      /* CSS styles for 16:9 displays */
      .video-container { max-width: 100%; }
    }
    ```

*   **Resolution (DPI):**
    *   `min-resolution`: Targets screens with a minimum pixel density (e.g., Retina displays).
    *   `dppx` (dots per pixel unit): Represents physical pixels per CSS pixel.
    *   `dpi` (dots per inch).

    ```css
    /* For high-resolution (Retina) displays */
    @media screen and (min-resolution: 2dppx) {
      /* CSS styles for high-DPI screens */
      img.logo { content: url('logo@2x.png'); }
    }
    ```

### Combining Multiple Conditions

Media queries can be combined using logical operators:

*   `and`: Combines multiple media features. All conditions must be true.
*   `or` (`,` comma): A comma-separated list of media queries. If any one of the media queries is true, the styles are applied.
*   `not`: Negates the entire media query. Rarely used with `and`.
*   `only`: Hides the style sheet from older browsers that do not support media queries.

    ```css
    /* Applied for landscape viewports at least 30em wide */
    @media screen and (min-width: 30em) and (orientation: landscape) {
      .sidebar { width: 25%; }
    }

    /* Device-specific breakpoints (ranges) */
    @media (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 991px) {
      /* Styles for small tablets and large phones */
      .container {
        max-width: 750px;
      }
    }

    @media (min-width: 992px) and (max-width: 1199px) {
      /* Styles for medium devices (tablets, small laptops) */
      .container {
        max-width: 970px;
      }
    }

    @media (min-width: 1200px) {
      /* Styles for large devices (desktops, large laptops) */
      .container {
        max-width: 1170px;
      }
    }
    ```

**Best Practices for Breakpoints:**

Instead of device-specific breakpoints, it's often more effective to use content-based breakpoints. This means adjusting your layout where the content starts to look bad, rather than targeting specific device widths. Common breakpoints often align with general device categories (e.g., mobile, tablet, desktop) as seen in frameworks like Bootstrap, but fluid layouts and flexible content can make a stricter `device-width` approach less necessary.

`em` and `rem` units are generally preferred for breakpoints over `px` because they scale with the user's default font size settings, offering better accessibility.

